Feature: a launched bc-base BC carries gh and agent-vault resolvable on PATH

  Regression guard (lead-h755). The gh-missing / credential class of bootstrap
  failures (cf. lead-b6f2, the gh dummy-credential fix) motivated pinning that
  the bootstrap tooling a launched BC depends on is actually resolvable inside
  the running container, not merely baked into the image layer. This scenario
  pins the runtime-PATH invariant: in a launched bc-base BC, "gh" and
  "agent-vault" both resolve on PATH ("command -v" succeeds). It is the launched-
  container runtime observable, complementing the build-time image-content pins
  (scenario 42 @scenario_hash:ccb145d71c7100a2 — bc-base installs shop-templates;
  scenario 53 @scenario_hash:69904daef7a8d13e — rebuilt :latest carries released
  dep versions) and distinct from the host-side CLI-PATH pin (scenario 17
  @scenario_hash:a876c34e9c93ee43 — bc-container on host PATH).

  SCOPE EXCLUSION: docker is intentionally NOT asserted here. bc-base carries no
  docker CLI by design; this guard covers gh and agent-vault only and must not be
  read to require docker on PATH. (Targets shopsystem-bc-launcher / bc-base.)

  @scenario_hash:04f2c7501273705c
  Scenario: a launched bc-base BC has gh and agent-vault resolvable on PATH
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And bc-container launch is run with BC name "shopsystem-messaging"
    And the container "bc-shopsystem-messaging" is running on the pinned bc-base image
    When "command -v gh" and "command -v agent-vault" are executed inside that running container
    Then each command exits zero and prints an executable path for "gh" and for "agent-vault" respectively
